                  alfe — autolisp-front-end implementation plan
                  =============================================

Goal
----

Rewrite the historical bash `autolisp-script` wrapper as a single
Common Lisp executable named `alfe` (= AutoLISP Front-End), built on
top of the `clautolisp/autolisp-*` modules. The new binary unifies
three backends behind one CLI:

  - `clautolisp` in-process  (default, no CAD required) ;
  - `clautolisp` subprocess  (isolation; runs `clautolisp-sbcl` under
                              `uiop:launch-program`) ;
  - `bricscad` / `autocad`   (file-IPC protocol; the only IPC
                              available inside a CAD-resident
                              AutoLISP REPL).

Specification lives in
  `autolisp-front-end/documentation/alfe--specifications.org`,
copied from the upstream `autolisp-script` spec and updated for the
new architecture. Read that document first; this plan summarises the
*work* needed to land it.

Why the split between backends matters
--------------------------------------

The architectural fault line is: *can the backend offer IPC other
than files?*

  - clautolisp: yes — it is a Common Lisp process; alfe binds the
    evaluator in-process, or pipes stdin/stdout if a separate Lisp
    image is preferred. No file protocol is involved. The workdir is
    used only for logs and `--dry-run` symmetry.

  - BricsCAD / AutoCAD: no — the AutoLISP REPL lives behind a GUI,
    AutoLISP has neither sockets nor pipes nor shared memory, and the
    only side channel is the file system. The file-IPC protocol
    (`stdin.txt` / `stdout.txt` / `stderr.txt` / `status.txt` /
    `control.txt` / `heartbeat.txt` under `WORKDIR/protocol/`) is
    therefore *forced*, not a design choice.

Concretely:

  - the runtime AutoLISP that lives inside the CAD process
    (`autolisp-remote-io.lsp`) is kept *as-is* — it is the AutoLISP
    code that talks to the file slots from the CAD side ;
  - the *driver* of that protocol — the bash code in
    `lib/autolisp-remote-io.sh` — is what gets rewritten in CL, as
    part of alfe.

Modules from clautolisp that alfe directly consumes
---------------------------------------------------

  autolisp-reader        source-form reading + completeness checks
                         (for `--interactive` multi-line forms).
  autolisp-runtime       evaluator, contexts, dialects, error
                         conditions, source-positions.
  autolisp-builtins-core printing, list, string, file, stream
                         builtins available under every backend.
  autolisp-host          HAL contract; alfe wires `MockHost` by
                         default for `--clautolisp`.
  autolisp-mock-host     concrete mock host used by `--host mock`.

Phasing and dependencies
------------------------

  Phase 0 — Foundations
    alfe-skeleton.issue              (ASDF, packages, version, build,
                                       Make targets)
    alfe-cli.issue                   (argv → action plan → exit code)
    alfe-backend-interface.issue     (abstract backend protocol)

  Phase 1 — clautolisp backend (end-to-end)
    alfe-backend-clautolisp.issue    (in-process + subprocess)
       blocked by Phase 0

  Phase 2 — CAD backends share-the-protocol
    alfe-file-protocol.issue         (atomic writes, status polling,
                                       line-to-form reader, runtime
                                       bootstrap emission)
       blocked by Phase 0

  Phase 3 — Per-CAD backends
    alfe-backend-bricscad.issue      (macOS/Linux batch, Windows COM)
    alfe-backend-autocad.issue       (Windows COM, accoreconsole batch)
       blocked by Phase 2

  Phase 4 — Quality & spec
    alfe-conformance.issue           (scenario corpus, parity tests
                                       against the bash wrapper, spec
                                       maintenance)
       runs continuously; meaningfully gated by Phase 1

Migration path from the bash wrapper
------------------------------------

The bash wrapper stays in place during the transition; alfe lands
backend-by-backend behind a feature flag (`$ALFE_BACKEND_OVERRIDE`)
that lets early adopters opt in per backend. The `alfe-conformance`
ticket includes parity tests: run the same scenario through the bash
`autolisp` and the new `alfe`, assert identical stdout/stderr/status
where the contract requires it. Divergences are either documented
(e.g. messages that the bash version produced via shell artifacts and
that alfe replaces with structured Lisp output) or fixed.

The CAD-side AutoLISP runtime (`autolisp-remote-io.lsp`) is reused
verbatim. Only the *driver* (the bash) is rewritten.

V1 success criteria
-------------------

  - `alfe --version` returns the new version string and exits 0.
  - `alfe --clautolisp -x '(+ 1 2)'` runs in-process and prints 3.
  - `alfe --clautolisp -i` opens an interactive REPL with multi-line
    forms (handled by `autolisp-reader`).
  - On a machine with BricsCAD installed,
      `alfe --bricscad -l SCRIPT.lsp`
    drives the CAD via the file protocol and exits with the script's
    final status.
  - The autolisp-test conformance corpus runs green against
    `alfe --clautolisp --host mock`.
  - The alfe-conformance parity suite shows no regression against
    the bash wrapper for the listed invariants of the spec.

V2 / out of scope here
----------------------

  - GUI front-end for alfe (DCL or OpenDCL). Distinct subproject.
  - `vlisp-compile` outside `--autocad --mode automation` on Windows.
  - EPURE-style user-specific plugin features — keep the spec hook
    but defer the plugin model.
  - Native Windows COM-without-shell path. The Windows backends keep
    their VBScript bridges in V1; a future ticket can move them to a
    pure-CL COM client (`cffi` + `OAIDispatch`).

